  description: "Free AI image generator (formerly DALL-E mini) that creates unique artwork from text prompts with multiple style options.",
  fullDescription: "Craiyon is a popular free AI art generator that transforms text descriptions into unique images in seconds, originally launched as DALL-E mini in 2021 before rebranding to Craiyon in 2022 [citation:10]. Developed by CEO Boris Dayma and the core team, Craiyon makes AI image generation accessible to everyone with no login required for basic use, democratizing creative expression for millions of users worldwide. The platform uses advanced diffusion technology that starts with random noise and gradually refines it into the desired image, guided by the user's text description [citation:10]. The underlying model was trained on millions of images from the internet, learning relationships between concepts, styles, and visual elements to generate entirely new images rather than retrieving existing ones. Users can generate images by typing descriptive prompts—the more specific the details, the better the results. Style options include Photo (photorealistic), Illustration (artistic), Vector (graphic design), and Raw (minimal processing). Aspect ratio choices include square, landscape, and portrait formats, with subscribers getting additional options [citation:10]. The 'Exclude' field allows users to specify what they don't want in images (e.g., 'people', 'text', 'blue colors'), giving finer control over results. Free users access Base quality images (good quality, square only, watermarked, may experience wait times). Subscribers access Pro quality (higher detail, sharpness, accuracy), unlimited Base images, all aspect ratios, no watermarks, priority generation, high-quality downloads, and early access to features [citation:10]. Images generated through Craiyon can be used for personal, academic, or commercial purposes as long as terms of use are respected, with free users requested to credit craiyon.com [citation:10]. The team acknowledges that like all AI models trained on internet data, Craiyon can reflect societal biases present in its training data, and they are actively working to identify and reduce these biases through ongoing research [citation:10]. With millions of users and a commitment to keeping free access available (supported by paid subscribers), Craiyon remains one of the most accessible entry points for anyone curious about AI image generation, from beginners exploring creativity to professionals needing quick visual concepts.",
